article.description: Sue Bird is nursing a knee injury and her scoring is down. So how come the Seattle Storm locker room is full of smiles?
article.headline: Bird gets teammates in flow, Storm win third in row
article.linkText: Hurt Bird? Nobody could tell as Storm roll on
article.story:
SEATTLE (AP) -- Sue Bird is nursing a knee injury and her scoring
is down. So how come the Seattle Storm locker room is full of
smiles?
	   Because the All-Star point guard is still getting her teammates
open looks and they have started making them, particularly fellow
All-Star forward Lauren Jackson, who scored 20 points Tuesday night
in Seattle's 78-51 over the Indiana Fever.
	   It was the third straight win for Seattle (3-3), which used a
balanced offense to pull away midway through the first half en
route to a season-high point total. Three Storm players scored in
double figures and all but one scored at least two points.
	   Bird finished with seven points and eight assists. The Storm
started the season 0-3 with Bird shouldering much of the scoring
load. However, since Bird's injury, her teammates have been forced
to contribute more and Seattle's offense has improved.
	   Jackson, who was named WNBA player of the week earlier Tuesday,
posted her third straight 20-point game, making nine of 12 shots,
including two of three 3-pointers.
	   Despite turning in three solid performances after a shaky start,
Jackson insists she has not found her groove yet. The third-year
player from Australia said better play from her teammates makes her
look good.
	   ``I haven't played that great,'' Jackson said. ``I'm doing all
right. As a team we're great.''
	   Seattle also dominated the Fever (2-2) with a stiff defense
effort. The Storm held Indiana to a franchise-low 18 first-half
points.
	   ``They played extremely good defense,'' Indiana coach Nell
Fortner said. ``We had a stretch in the first half where we had
five turnovers in a row ... we just didn't have any momentum after
that.''
	   The Storm cruised in the second half and Indiana never got
closer than 16.
	   Sandy Brondello added 11 points for Seattle and Kamila
Vodichkova had 10.
	   Tamika Catchings and Stephanie White had 13 points each for
Indiana. It was a season low for Catchings, who injured her left
ankle in the first half when she landed on Bird's foot while
chasing after a loose ball. She went to the locker room for
treatment and then returned in the second half to score 10 points.
	   In the Storm's first three games, Bird averaged 17.3 points, 7.3
assists and 2.0 turnovers per game, but the rest of the team shot
33.3 percent. In the past three games, all wins, Bird has averaged
6.5 points and 7.6 assists and Seattle has shot 46 percent.
	   ``My teammates get all the credit,'' Bird said. ``They're
stepping up and that makes us a better team.''
